Aelfwent|The Aelfwent|Ts'i Suhyasei	A river flowing within the Aldheorte forest. It runs parallel to the inlet stream from Geloë's lake and passes through the Sithi city of Da'ai Chikiza. Its Erkynlandish name means "Sithi River," while its Sithi name, Ts'i Suhyasei, is translated by Binabik as "Her Blood is Cool."
Aldheorte|The Aldheorte Forest	The great forest covering much of central Osten Ard. Its name means "Old heart," and it contains ancient Sithi places such as Da'ai Chikiza as well as hidden waters, wild paths, and deep regions beyond ordinary settlement.
Asu'a	One of the Sithi Nine Cities and, after Tumet'ai was lost, the first and greatest city of the Sithi. When occupied, it was renowned for beauty, with flowering meadows to the north and many lakes in the surrounding land. The city stands at the heart of the oldest Sithi presence in Osten Ard.
Commeis Valley	A valley of Nabban known as a gateway into the duchy. Its valley floor is crowded with settlements and towns, and its hills are thick with whitewashed stone houses. It is connected with the Anitullean Road and the approach to Onestrine Pass.
Crannhyr	A walled coastal city in Hernystir. In older days the community was called Da-Yoshoga, or Goblin Rock, and the place preserves traces of older inhabitants and older names beneath its Hernystiri identity.
Da'ai Chikiza	One of the Sithi Nine Cities, an abandoned Sithi city on the Aelfwent River on the east side of the Wealdhelm in Aldheorte. Its hidden, ancient character links it closely to the forest's Sithi past and to the older roads and rivers of Osten Ard.
Enki-e-Shao'saye	The Summer City of the Sithi, one of the Sithi Nine Cities, standing in the southeastern corner of Aldheorte forest near the border of the High Thrithings grasslands. It was once a thriving Sithi city and remains an important name in the geography of the Gardenborn.
Erchester	The capital city of Erkynland, adjacent to the Hayholt. It is the chief city of the kingdom and part of the political and royal center of Osten Ard.
Erkynland	A kingdom on the western coast of Osten Ard, ruled from the Hayholt. It is bounded by Hernystir, Rimmersgard, Aldheorte, the Thrithings, and Nabban, making it a central political region between many peoples, roads, forests, rivers, and borderlands.
Falshire	A wool-producing city in Erkynland, southeast of Erchester. Its prosperity and civic life are tied to the wool trade, placing it among the significant Erkynlandish towns and cities beyond the Hayholt.
Gadrinsett	A squatter town near the junction of the Stefflod and Ymstrecca, settled by refugees from Erkynland. Its rough origin as a refuge settlement gives it a different character from the older cities and baronies of the realm.
Gleniwent	A river of Erkynland flowing through Kynslagh and emptying into the ocean at Meremund. Its course connects the lake country around the Hayholt with the coastal geography of Meremund and the northern mouth of the river.
Green Angel Tower|Angel	The Sithi-built main tower of the Hayholt, once the tallest tower of Asu'a and the last remnant of the old Sithi city visible above ground. Also formerly called Nightingale Tower, it is described as cloud-tall, with white walls, a bell tower of tall arched openings, and stairs that climb upward as well as descend deep beneath the city. Its place at the heart of the Hayholt ties it to the ancient Gardenborn past beneath Erkynland's royal castle.
Hayholt	The great castle of Erkynland, standing above Kynslagh Bay and the city of Erchester. Built over the ruins of the former Sithi city Asu'a, it contains layers of construction from several peoples and ages, including a vast hidden labyrinth of older Sithi and Dwarrow structures beneath its human halls. Its most famous surviving remnant of Sithi architecture is Green Angel Tower, and its position makes it the royal and political heart of Osten Ard.
Hernystir	A largely mountainous kingdom bordering Erkynland to the west. Although nominally independent, it acknowledges the suzerainty of the High King. Its people are described as pagan, and its chief places include Hernysadharc, Crannhyr, Nad Mullach, Abaingeat, Ballacym, and Cathyn Dair.
Hikehikayo	One of the Sithi Nine Cities, an abandoned Dwarrow city beneath Rimmersgard's Vestivegg Mountains. After the parting of the Sithi and Norns, Jenjiyana of the Nightingales declared it one of the cities given to the Tinukeda'ya.
Jao é-Tinukai'i	A hidden Sithi settlement deep in the Aldheorte, its name meaning "Boat on the Ocean of Trees." It is made of elaborate fabric rather than stone and is woven into the forest itself. Notable features include Shao Irigú, the Summer Gate of two towering hemlocks, and the Yásira, a great tent raised around a vast ash tree.
Jhiná T'seneí	One of the Sithi Nine Cities, now beneath the southern seas. After the parting of the Sithi and Norns, Jenjiyana of the Nightingales declared it one of the cities given to the Tinukeda'ya.
Kementari	One of the Sithi Nine Cities, apparently on or near Warinsten. It is associated with Benayha and with the ancient geography of the Gardenborn, though its exact fate is uncertain.
Kwanitupul	A large trading city at the edge of the Wran. It began as a small trading village and grew when merchants from the Southern Islands, Perdruin, and Nabban made use of its position near the marshlands and waterways.
Kynslagh|Kynslagh Lake	The lake on whose shore stands the Hayholt. Its position beside the great castle ties it to the royal and legendary geography of Erkynland.
M'yin Azoshai	A hill and the site of Hernysadharc. It was given to Hern after a dispute arising from Azosha's bequest of the land to Hern's mortal people, linking the place to ancient dealings between mortals and the Sithi.
Meremund	A city in Erkynland on the northern mouth of the Gleniwent, opposite Wentmouth. It is associated with the Prince Regent Elias and with Princess Miriamele's early life.
Mezutu'a|The Silverhome	One of the Sithi Nine Cities, known as the Silverhome, located beneath the Grianspog Mountains. It is still occupied by a small group of Dwarrow and includes named places such as the Arena and Pattern Hall. After the parting of the Sithi and Norns, Jenjiyana of the Nightingales declared Mezutu'a to be given to the Tinukeda'ya.
Mintahoq (Village)|Mintahoq	A Qanuc village in Yiqanuc, birthplace of Binabik and domain of the Qanuc folk. It is effectively governed by the Herder and the Huntress, Uammannaq and Nunuuika, and stands as one of the central named settlements of the Trollfells.
Misty Vale|Tanakirú	A valley deep in the heart of Aldheorte Forest, called Tanakirú in the Zida'ya language. It is associated with strange forest lore, including the Uro'eni, the Ogre of Misty Vale.
Naarved|Naarvad	A city in Rimmersgard, the cold northern land of the Rimmersmen. Also called Naarvad, it is one of the named settlements of that region, belonging to the same northern geography as Elvritshalla, Saegard, Skoggey, Tungoldyr, Hullnir, and the lands beneath Stormspike.
Nabban (city)|City of Nabban	The capital and largest city of the Duchy of Nabban. It is the chief urban center of Nabbanai power and one of the principal cities of Osten Ard.
Nabban (duchy)|Duchy of Nabban	A city and duchy on the central western coast of Osten Ard. The duchy is one of the major human powers of the continent, with its capital, outer baronies, valleys, bays, roads, and noble houses forming a distinct Nabbanai political and cultural world.
Naglimund|Ujin e-d'a Sikhunae	A fortress and town in northern Erkynland at the base of the Wealdhelm. Domain of Prince Josua, it bears the grey swan as banner and sigil and is said to be a place of great power, comparable in some ways to a Master Witness.
Nakkiga	The Norn city inside Stormspike, carved into the mountain as the hidden seat of Hikeda'ya power. It is one of the central places of Norn history, culture, and rule in the far North.
Nakkiga-That-Was	One of the Sithi Nine Cities, a ruined Norn city at the foot of Stormspike. It was abandoned when the Norns moved into the caverns they carved beneath the mountain, the place also called Nakkiga.
Naraxi|Naraxi Island	An island nation at the southern end of the Bay of Firannos. Its culture is associated with piracy, mercenaries, and slavery, and its people are described as dark-skinned and dark-haired, with an exotic language.
Nascadu	A desert region in the southernmost reaches of Osten Ard. It is described as a dry, barren wasteland of sand dunes, inhabited by creatures such as apes, lions, and sand snakes.
New Gadrinsett	A refuge settlement on Sesuad'ra, named after Gadrinsett in the valley to the west. It is a gathered community rather than an old city, shaped by displacement, hardship, and the need for shelter in a dangerous time.
Osten Ard	The world in which Memory, Sorrow and Thorn takes place. It is a vast land of varied terrain and climate, containing human kingdoms, Gardenborn ruins, forests, mountains, rivers, bays, deserts, marshes, ancient roads, and hidden places.
Pelippa's Bowl	An inn in Kwanitupul named for Saint Pelippa because it was run by Xorastra, a woman who had once been a nun of Pelippa's order. Large and undistinguished-looking, it stands in a backwater part of the warehouse district beneath a sign with a golden bowl.
Perdruin	An island duchy west of Nabban, ruled from Ansis Pelippé. Its position off the coast gives it a distinctive maritime and political role among the powers of Osten Ard.
Rimmersgard	The land of the Rimmersmen in northern Osten Ard. It is a cold northern region associated with Elvritshalla, Naarved, Saegard, Skoggey, Tungoldyr, Hullnir, and the lands in the shadow of Stormspike.
Sesuad'ra|Stone of Farewell	The Stone of Farewell, south of Enki-e-Shao'saye, standing atop Rhao iye-Sama'an five hundred cubits above the river. It is the site of the parting of Sithi and Norns and one of the most important ancient places in Osten Ard.
Sithi Nine Cities|The Nine Gardenborn Cities	The nine great cities founded by the Gardenborn after they fled Venyha Do'sae, the Lost Garden. They were masterworks as well as homes for the Sithi, Norns, and their kin: Asu'a, Da'ai Chikiza, Enki-e-Shao'saye, Hikehikayo, Jhiná T'seneí, Kementari, Mezutu'a, Nakkiga-That-Was, and Tumet'ai.
Sovebek	An abandoned town in the White Waste, east of Saint Skendi's monastery. Its location places it among the bleak northern Erkynlandish settlements near the edge of the great forest and the waste.
Stormspike|Vihyuyaq	A mountain in the North and home of the Norns. The city of Nakkiga is located inside the mountain, making Stormspike both a natural feature and the center of Hikeda'ya power.
The Knock|Knock|Ereb Irgú	A grassy dipping place in Aldheorte, called Ereb Irgú or Western Gate by the Sithi. It was the site of a major battle between Hernystiri and Rimmersmen during the Rimmersman invasions of Osten Ard, and its common name is thought to come from the Rimmersman Knokkegard, "the Boneyard."
The Road of Dreams	A mystical dream realm in which those who can travel there are able to communicate with one another and discover truths about the world. It is a place of vision, contact, and hidden knowledge rather than an ordinary road.
The White Waste|White Waste	A permafrost region north of Aldheorte Forest in Erkynland. It is one of the bleak northern reaches of Osten Ard.
Tumet'ai	One of the Sithi Nine Cities, initially the first city and greatest of the Sithi cities before snow and ice overtook it. It was noted for sunrise vistas and tall towers visible from miles away when painted red by the dawn.
Urmsheim|Yijarjuk|The Mountain of Urmsheim	A dragon mountain north of the White Waste, called Yijarjuk in Qanuc. It is associated with the great white dragon Igjarjuk and with journeys into the dangerous northern highlands.
Utanyeat|The Earldom of Utanyeat	An earldom in northwestern Erkynland on the east bank of the Greenwade, described as the westernmost tip of Erkynland. It is associated with Earl Guthwulf and the borderland geography of the High King's realm.
Venyha Do'sae|The Garden|The Lost Garden	The ancestral home of the Gardenborn across the Dreaming Sea, also called the Garden that is Vanished, the Lost Garden, or simply the Garden. It is remembered as a place of mountains, valleys, wild witchwood groves, the living Dreaming Sea, and origins shared by the Sithi, Norns, and Tinukeda'ya.
Village Grove	Tiamak's native village in the Wran. It is one of the named settlements of the Wrannamen, tied to marsh life, boats, stilted dwellings, and the customs of Tiamak's people.
Vinitta|Vinitta Island	An island in the Bay of Firannos, birthplace of Camaris and the Benidrivine House. Its notable features include a harbor and docks.
Warinsten|Warinsten Island	An island off the coast of Erkynland and the birthplace of Prester John. Its place in the geography of Osten Ard is tied to the High King's origins.
Wentmouth	A castle fortress of rock on a hilltop at the southern mouth of the Gleniwent, opposite Meremund. It is described as "nothing but a hill and a harbor flame," suggesting a fortress-like settlement rather than a conventional city.
Wran	A marshy region forming the eastern coast of the Bay of Firannos and inhabited by the Wrannamen. It is a vast tangle of watercourses, mangroves, sandbars, trees, grasses, tropical storms, crocodiles, ghants, birds, water beetles, snakes, crabs, fish, and tree-dwelling animals.
Yiqanuc	The mountainous homeland of the Qanuc. It is associated with the Trollfells, Qanuc villages such as Mintahoq, and the high northern culture of the people humans often call trolls.
